BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 727.00 Td (our genes. It was John Bowlby’s stroke of genius that brought him to the realization that we’ve been) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 713.25 Td (programmed by evolution to single out a few specific individuals in our lives and make them precious to) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 699.50 Td (us. We’ve been bred to be dependent on a significant other. The need starts in the womb and ends) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 685.75 Td (when we die. Bowlby proposed that throughout evolution, genetic selection favored people who) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 672.00 Td (became attached because it provided a survival advantage. In prehistoric times, people who relied only) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 658.25 Td (on themselves and had no one to protect them were more likely to end up as prey. More often than not,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 644.50 Td (those who were with somebody who deeply cared about them survived to pass on to their offspring the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 630.75 Td (preference to form intimate bonds. In fact, the need to be near someone special is so important that the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 617.00 Td (brain has a biological mechanism specifical y responsible for creating and regulating our connection) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 603.25 Td (with our attachment figures \(parents, children, and romantic partners\). This mechanism, cal ed the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 589.50 Td (attachment system, consists of emotions and behaviors that ensure that we remain safe and protected) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 575.75 Td (by staying close to our loved ones. The mechanism explains why a child parted from his or her mother) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 562.00 Td (becomes frantic, searches wildly, or cries uncontrol ably until he or she reestablishes contact with her.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 542.25 Td (These reactions are coined protest behavior, and we al stil exhibit them as grown-ups. In prehistoric) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 528.50 Td (times, being close to a partner was a matter of life and death, and our attachment system developed to) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 514.75 Td (treat such proximity as an absolute necessity.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 495.00 Td (Imagine hearing news of a plane crash in the Atlantic on the evening your partner is flying from New) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 481.25 Td (York to London. That sinking feeling in the pit of your stomach and the accompanying hysteria you’d) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 467.50 Td (feel would be your attachment system at work. Your frantic cal s to the airport would be your protest) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 453.75 Td (behavior.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 434.00 Td (An extremely important aspect of evolution is heterogeneity.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 414.25 Td (Humans are a very heterogeneous species, varying greatly in appearance, attitudes, and behaviors.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 400.50 Td (This accounts to a great extent for our abundance and for our ability to fit into almost any ecological) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 386.75 Td (niche on earth. If we were al identical, then any single environmental chal enge would have the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 373.00 Td (potential to wipe us al out. Our variability improves the chances that a segment of the population that is) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 359.25 Td (unique in some way might survive when others wouldn’t. Attachment style is no different from any) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 345.50 Td (other human characteristic. Although we al have a basic need to form close bonds, the way we create) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 331.75 Td (them varies. In a very dangerous environment, it would be less advantageous to invest time and energy) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 318.00 Td (in just one person because he or she would not likely be around for too long; it would make more sense) Tj ET
BT /F1 11 Tf 54.00 304.25 Td (to get less attached and move on \(and hence, the avoidant attachment style\). Another option in a harsh) Tj ET
